            <p:rationale>The service-oriented paradigm is not ideal for all logical integration between applications, regardless of the reusability of this integration. This style is based on the fact that an application provides a service using other systems by calling this service. Spreading transformed data (typically master data) is different in nature; the reusability and the initiative of the communication is just the system that manages the data.  It is not the service that is centralized, but the published data. This is called the event-based paradigm because the occurrence of the change is actually an event that should be published to all applications (including a redundant copy of the data). In addition to the definition of the main event, unlike a service definition, one could talk about a (reusable) event definition. Using a publish/subscribe communication method, it is relatively easy to add these definitions without the need to know the source administration. </p:rationale>
            <p:implications>A distinction is made between links that follow the service oriented paradigm and links that follow the event-based paradigm. For each data which is an associated event, a definition is drawn up by a published topic. Redundancy also copies existing New applications and manages copies of data subscribed to those changes.</p:implications>
